&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by the [bold]Industrial Communities Alliance[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Industrial Communities Alliance[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The Industrial Communities Alliance is the all-party 
[normal]association of local authorities in the industrial areas of England, Scotland and Wales.  The Alliance was formed in 2007 by the merger of longer-standing associations dating back to the 1980s.  The Alliance
[normal] works with the Westminster government, the devol
[normal]ved administrations and the EU to deliver
[normal] policies and funding 
[normal]that
[normal] support economic and social regeneration.  Some 60 local authorities are currently members.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Welfare reform has been a regular topic of discussion at regional and national meetings of the 
[normal]Alliance.  The present submission draws on these discussions and on published academic evidenc
[normal]e to illustrate the
[normal] impact 
[normal]that 
[normal]welfare reform in general, and reform to housing benefits in particular, is having in much of older industrial Britain.  The submi
[normal]ssion was prepared by staff in the National Secretariat and endorsed by the Alliance Executive, comprising senior elected members from around the country.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Context[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Britain’s older industrial areas include some of the most economically deprived parts of t
[normal]he UK.  Over many years, substantial parts of Scotland, Wales and the North of England, and even some areas further south, have seen the decline of the industries on which their economies and communities were once based.  Coal, steel, shipbuilding and text
[normal]iles, for example, have now disappeared entirely from some places and survive only on a much diminished scale in others.  This has cast a long shadow over economic and social well-being.  Reg
[normal]eneration efforts have brought
[normal] new jobs, but rarely on a sufficie
[normal]nt scale
[normal] to offset previous job losses.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The result is that Britain’s older industrial areas mostly suffer from high levels of worklessness.  Even in the years prior to the 2008 recession, they remained a long way off ful
[normal]l employment.  The worklessness
[normal] is 
[normal]far more extensive than just conventional ‘un
[normal]employment’.  For example,
[normal] one of the long-term consequences of a weak demand for labour 
[normal]in older industrial Britain 
[normal]has been that very large numbers of men and women with health problems or disabilities have en
[normal]ded up 
[normal]parked outside of the labour market on incapacity benefits.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The consequence is
[normal] that individuals
[normal] are more likely to be out-of-work on benefits in older industrial Britain than in more prosperous local economies.  Because of lower wages for those in 
[normal]work, they are also more likely to draw on in-work benefits.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Welfare reform
[normal] te
[normal]nds to be discussed with little
[normal] reference to its impact in specific places up and down the country.  However, because benefit claimant rates va
[normal]ry so much across Britain,
[normal] the pla
[normal]ces where claimants are concentrated – such as older industrial areas – are 
[normal]clearly 
[normal]most exposed to financial losses.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Case study: under-occupation of social housing (‘bedroom tax’)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]To illustrate the disproportionate impact of welfa
[normal]re reform
[normal] on olde
[normal]r 
[normal]industrial areas
[normal] it is worth looking at the new under-occupation rules governing support for housing costs in 
[normal]the social rented sector, generally
[normal] known as the ‘bedroom tax’.  The rules on under-occupation are of course the same across the who
[normal]le country but
[normal] the impact differs
[normal] from place to place for two 
[normal]main 
[normal]reasons.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]First, the 
[normal]share of the housing stock 
[normal]in the social rented sector
[normal] varies a great deal across the country.  This often reflect
[normal]s
[normal] complex historical reasons – the aftermath of the redevelopment of slum housing for example, and t
[normal]he differing priority that
[normal] authorities once attached to building council houses.  Older industrial Britain, with a legacy of slum clearance and a tradit
[normal]ion o
[normal]f municipal activism,
[normal] has some of the highest proportions of social housing.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Second, the 
[normal]proportion of working-age households who claim Housing Benefit
[normal] varies according to the scale of worklessness and the extent of low wages.  Older industrial Britain 
[normal]is
[normal] among the places where the claimant rate is highest.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 1 shows the estimated impact of the ‘bedroom tax’ by district across the whole of Great Britain.  The figures here are taken from a report by Sheffield Hallam University
[normal], publis
[normal]hed earlier in 2
[normal]013, and are
[normal] ultimately rooted in the Treasury’s own estimates of the financial savings and in DWP benefits data for 
[normal]local areas.  T
[normal]he map shows the 
[normal]annual 
[normal]financial loss 
[normal]per adult of working age – i.e. averaging the financial loss across the whole working
[normal] age population of each area, inclu
[normal]ding non-claimants
[normal].  This is the best measure of the intensity of the financial ‘hit’ in each part of the country.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Anyone familiar with the economic geo
[normal]graphy of Britain will see that 
[normal]the areas hit hardest by the ‘bedroo
[normal]m tax’
[normal] include
[normal] the industrial areas of northern England, the Welsh Valleys, the Birmingham and Glasgow areas and a number of inner London boroughs.  By contrast, substantial parts of the south and east of England outside London are relatively lightly affec
[normal]ted.
[normal]&#xa0;
