[normal]To und
[normal]erline
[normal] t
[normal]he highly uneven impact of
[normal] the 
[normal]‘
[normal]bedroom tax
[normal]’, Table 1 shows a range of figur
[normal]es for each of the GB regions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The first column shows that i
[normal]n total
[normal] 660,000 households are thought to
[normal] be affected
[normal] – the Department fo
[normal]r Work and Pensions own
[normal] figure
[normal] – but of these
[normal] just 40,000 are in the South East of England, compared to 240,000 in the thre
[normal]e regions of northern England.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The second column shows that t
[normal]he annual financial loss to Housing Benefit claimants in the 
[normal]South East totals £30m.
[normal] 
[normal] I
[normal]n 
[normal]the three re
[normal]gions of 
[normal]northern England
[normal] it totals
[normal] 
[normal]£160m.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The third column shows the proportion of households affected by the ‘bedroom tax’.  In the North East it affects 440 out of every 10,000 household
[normal]s
[normal] , four times as many as in the South East.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The fourth column av
[normal]erages the financial loss across the whole working age population (including non-claimants).  The loss is more than three times greater in the North E
[normal]ast than the South East.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The point here is that the
[normal] highly
[normal] uneven impact of the ’bedroom tax’ 
[normal]has largely
[normal] been overlooked.  Yet it is increasingly leading to widespread distress in some of the most disadvantaged communities in Britain.  According to reports to Alliance na
[normal]tional meetings
[normal], the ‘bedroom tax’ is leading to a sharp rise in rent arrears, to high le
[normal]vels of demand for smaller accommodation that is 
[normal]simply  not available, and to
[normal] difficulty in 
[normal]letting 
[normal]the 
[normal]larger properties owned by housing associations and councils.  Local authorities are als
[normal]o aware that a move from social-
[normal]rented housing to smaller but m
[normal]ore expensive accommodation in the private-rented sector would not normally reduce benefit payments.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Other reforms to housing support[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]T
[normal]he evidence on the other elements
[normal] of support for housing costs 
[normal]confirms an
[normal] uneven impact across the country, though not always in 
[normal]quite 
[normal]the same way as for the ‘bedroom tax’.  The Sheffield Hallam study, for example, indicates that the
[normal] household benefit cap
[normal] impact
[normal]s
[normal] to a major extent 
[normal]only in London, where
[normal] rent levels 
[normal]have hithert
[normal]o driven up Housing Benefit entitlement
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The reforms to
[normal] Local Housing Allowanc
[normal]e
[normal], 
[normal]which apply to the private-
[normal]rented sector
[normal],
[normal] impact on London because of high rent levels but quite a number of older industrial areas in the North West, Yorkshire and North Eas
[normal]t are also badly affected because of the high proporti
[normal]on of tenants
[normal] out-of-work or on low wages.
[normal]  There are reports
[normal] that in some places private landlords have become nervous about letting or re-letting to Housing Benefit claimants and that this is feeding 
[normal]through to levels of homelessness.  Indeed, government figures show that the proportion of households citing loss of a private tenancy as the trigger for their homelessness is 
[normal]r
[normal]is
[normal]i
[normal]ng and now at an all-time high.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The impacts of the reforms to Council Tax 
[normal]Benefit are complex.  It might have been expected that older industrial areas would be hit hard because of hig
[normal]h worklessness
[normal].  In the event, the devolved administrations and a number of English local authorities, such County Durham and Northumberland, have
[normal] chosen not to pass on the reduction in government grant.  But as the Sheffield Hallam report shows, in the older industrial areas where the cut in government grant has been passed on in full the
[normal] financial losses
[normal] are among the largest in the country.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Look
[normal]ing a little further ah
[normal]ead, there are
[normal] worries that the intention to pay the ‘rent’ component of Universal Credit to claimants rather than direct to landlords, and to do so on a monthly rather than for
[normal]tnightly basis, will have damaging
[normal] repercussions for hou
[normal]sing associations and local councils.  The fear is that the financial pressures on tenants will mean that rent
[normal]s go unpaid and arrears
[normal] develop.  Since social landlords borrow against their anticipated income stream, this 
[normal]also 
[normal]has potential knock-on conseque
[normal]nces for 
[normal]the volume of 
[normal]new building.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The cumulative impact o[bold]n households[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]It would
[normal] be misleading
[normal] to take the housing-related benefit changes out of their wider context.
[normal]  Changes to
[normal] 
[normal]incapacity and disability benefits, 
[normal]to 
[normal]tax credits and 
[normal]to 
[normal]Child B
[normal]enefit
[normal] are underway at the same time
[normal], and 
[normal]in several cases are
[normal] substantially larger in terms
[normal] of their financial impact.  The effect is that
[normal] several d
[normal]ifferent elements to the
[normal] welfare reform package impact simultaneously on the same households and individuals.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It
[normal] is the 
[normal]cumulative
[normal] aspect of
[normal] the reforms 
[normal]that 
[normal]often 
[normal]make 
[normal]them so pernicious
[normal].  Drawing on official data, the Sheffield Hallam report quantifies the average annual loss
[normal],
[normal] per affected household or individual, when 
[normal]each of 
[normal]the reform
[normal]s has
[normal] come into full effect
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
