[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The point here is that some of the hous
[normal]eholds adversely affected by
[normal] reductions in housing support are also likely to find that that they will lose mo
[normal]ney as a result of other elements
[normal] of the reforms.  Indeed, this is already h
[normal]appening.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The group that is perhaps mo
[normal]st exposed to reductions in entitlement
[normal] are older working age couples who have hitherto combined entitlement to a number of b
[normal]enefits
[normal].  Many incapacity claimants, for example, also claim DLA, Housing Benefit and Counci
[normal]l Tax Benefit.  
[normal]Some of t
[normal]hose within this group 
[normal]who have lesser disabilities will
[normal] find that they are unable to claim Employment and Support Allowance or Perso
[normal]nal Independence Payments
[normal] and that they must now pay some Council Tax
[normal] for the first time
[normal].  If they
[normal] live in social housing and their children have moved away
[normal], which is ofte
[normal]n the case, the ‘bedroom tax’ 
[normal]will also come into play.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This group – older out-of-work couples – is especially numerous in many older industrial areas, where meaningful job opportuni
[normal]ties 
[normal]for them 
[normal]have long since dried up.  They will often find that the cumulative effect of the reforms is to push them down to the poverty line.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The overall impact on places[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Likewise, the 
[normal]cumulative 
[normal]impact of the reforms on specific places and local 
[normal]economies should be a major cause for concern.
[normal]&#xa0;
